4.10 Definition. An $r$-truncated homological spectral sequence is one defined up to and including the $E^{r}$-term, together with the differential $d^{r}:E^{r}_{t,i}\to E^{r}_{t-r-1,t+r}$. We do not require that $d^{r}\circ d^{r}=0$, so the $E^{r+1}$-term is defined in terms of the $r$-truncated spectral sequence only if $d^{r}$ is indeed a differential (see [BB1, Definition 4.11]). The cohomological version is similarly defined.
3.6 Definition. Let $\lambda$ be a fixed limit cardinal, and let $s{R}\text{-}{\mathcal{M}od}$ denote the full subcategory of ${\mathcal{S}}_{\ast}$ consisting of simplicial $R$-modules – that is, $R$-GEMs. For any $B\in s{R}\text{-}{\mathcal{M}od}$, the limit $L_{(I,B)}$ of $I$ copies of $PB$, all mapping by $p$ to a single copy of $B$: ${}L_{(I,B)}~{}:=~{}\ \lim\left(\{PB_{({i})}\}_{i\in I}~{}\xrightarrow{p}~{}B~{% }\right)$ will be called an elementary $R$-Stover space. An $R$-Stover space is any product of at most $\lambda$ elementary $R$-Stover spaces.
1.1 Definition. Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a pointed simplicial model category, and ${\mathcal{A}}$ a collection of (homotopy) group objects in ${\mathcal{C}}$. As in §0.2, we let $\mathbf{\Theta}_{{\mathcal{A}}}$ denote the full sub-simplicial category of ${\mathcal{C}}$ containing ${\mathcal{A}}$ and closed under finite products and loops. We assume that all objects in $\mathbf{\Theta}_{{\mathcal{A}}}$ are fibrant and cofibrant. A functor $\mathfrak{X}:\mathbf{\Theta}_{{\mathcal{A}}}\to{\mathcal{S}}_{\ast}$ into the category of pointed simplicial sets is called an ${\mathcal{A}}$-mapping algebra if it preserves all limits inside $\mathbf{\Theta}_{{\mathcal{A}}}$, including products and loops. This means if we denote the value of $\mathfrak{X}$ at $B\in\mathbf{\Theta}_{{\mathcal{A}}}$ by $\mathfrak{X}\{{B}\}\in{\mathcal{S}}_{\ast}$, the natural maps: ${}\mathfrak{X}\{{\prod_{i=1}^{N}\,B_{i}}\}~{}\to~{}\prod_{i=1}^{N}\,\mathfrak{% X}\{{B_{i}}\}\hskip 14.226378pt\text{and}\hskip 14.226378pt\mathfrak{X}\{{% \Omega B}\}~{}\to~{}\Omega\mathfrak{X}\{{B}\}$ are isomorphisms for all $B,B_{i}\in\mathbf{\Theta}_{{\mathcal{A}}}$, where $\Omega$ denotes the loop functor both in ${\mathcal{C}}$ and in ${\mathcal{S}}_{\ast}$ (see [Q, I, §2]). Similarly for any other limits in ${\mathcal{C}}$, where both the objects and the cone happen to be in $\mathbf{\Theta}_{{\mathcal{A}}}$. The category of ${\mathcal{A}}$-mapping algebras is denoted by ${\mathcal{M}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}$. Since this is a full subcategory of the category ${\mathcal{S}}_{\ast}^{\mathbf{\Theta}_{{\mathcal{A}}}}$ of all simplicial functors $\mathbf{\Theta}_{{\mathcal{A}}}\to{\mathcal{S}}_{\ast}$, the category ${\mathcal{M}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}$ is simplicially enriched (cf. [DK1, §1]). For ${\mathcal{A}}\subseteq{\mathcal{C}}$ as above, for any fixed $Y\in{\mathcal{C}}$ we obtain a realizable ${\mathcal{A}}$-mapping algebra $\mathfrak{M}_{{\mathcal{A}}}Y$ by setting $(\mathfrak{M}_{{\mathcal{A}}}X)\{{B}\}:=\operatorname{map}_{{\mathcal{C}}}(B,X)$ for each $B\in\mathbf{\Theta}_{{\mathcal{A}}}$. This defines a functor $\mathfrak{M}_{{\mathcal{A}}}:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{M}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}$. In particular, an ${\mathcal{A}}$-mapping algebra $\mathfrak{X}$ is free if it is an arbitrary coproduct (in ${\mathcal{M}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}$) of ${\mathcal{A}}$-mapping algebras of the form $\mathfrak{M}_{{\mathcal{A}}}B_{\alpha}$ for $B_{\alpha}\in\mathbf{\Theta}_{{\mathcal{A}}}$. Such free ${\mathcal{A}}$-mapping algebras are (homotopy) cogroup objects in ${\mathcal{M}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}$ – and hence in the simplicial category ${\mathcal{S}}_{\ast}^{\mathbf{\Theta}_{{\mathcal{A}}}}$ of all simplicial functors $\mathbf{\Theta}_{{\mathcal{A}}}\to{\mathcal{S}}_{\ast}$ (compare [BB2, Lemma 8.13]).
4.1 Definition. Let $\Gamma$ be the category enriched in $({\mathcal{S}et}_{\ast},\wedge)$ with object set $\{\mathbf{n}\}_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}$ and a single non-zero arrow $d_{k}:\mathbf{k}\to\mathbf{k}-\mathbf{1}$ for each $k\in\mathbb{Z}$, satisfying $d_{k-1}\circ d_{k}=o$ for all $k$. We denote by $[\mathbf{m},\mathbf{n}]$ (for $-\infty\leq m\leq n\leq\infty$) the obvious full subcategories of $\Gamma$. A chain complex in a pointed category ${\mathcal{C}}$ is a pointed functor $C_{\ast}:\Gamma\to{\mathcal{C}}$ (that is, a ${\mathcal{S}et}_{\ast}$-enriched functor), an $n$-window chain complex is a pointed functor $[\mathbf{k}+\mathbf{n},\mathbf{k}]\to{\mathcal{C}}$. As usual, we write $\partial_{n}:C_{n}\to C_{n-1}$ for $C_{\ast}(d_{n}):C_{\ast}(\mathbf{n})\to C_{\ast}(\mathbf{n}-\mathbf{1})$, and $Z_{n}C_{\ast}:=\operatorname{Ker}\,(\partial_{n})\subseteq C_{n}$, for the $n$-cycles object. The category of all chain complexes in ${\mathcal{C}}$ is denoted by ${\mathcal{C}}^{\Gamma}$, and similarly we denote by ${\mathcal{C}}^{[\mathbf{m},\mathbf{n}]}$ the category of truncated chain complexes ($-\infty\leq m\leq n\leq\infty$).
7.7 Definition. Since the first Postnikov section of an arbitrary topological space $K$ is modelled algebraically by its fundamental groupoid $\hat{\pi}_{1}K$, the mapping algebra $P^{1}\mathfrak{M}_{{\mathcal{A}}}Y$ is equivalent to a track category – that is, a category enriched in groupoids (see [Ba1, VI, §3] or [BB2, §2]). A track category ${\mathcal{E}}$ consists of two categories with the same object set ${\mathcal{O}}$: namely, ${\mathcal{E}}_{0}$ (the ordinary category underlying ${\mathcal{E}}$), and ${\mathcal{E}}_{1}$, where for every two objects $x,y\in{\mathcal{O}}$, ${\mathcal{E}}_{1}(x,y)$ is a groupoid, with maps $f:x\to y$ in ${\mathcal{E}}_{0}$ as objects, and a set ${\mathcal{E}}_{1}(f,g)$ of (invertible) $2$-cells $H:f\Rightarrow g$ from $s(H)=f:x\to y$ to $t(H)=g:x\to y$. The $2$-cells induce an equivalence relation on maps in ${\mathcal{E}}_{0}$, with quotient category $\operatorname{ho}{\mathcal{E}}$, the homotopy category of ${\mathcal{E}}$.
3.14 Definition. Note that a realizable discrete ${\mathcal{A}}$-mapping algebra $\mathfrak{X}:=\mathfrak{M}_{{\mathcal{A}}}^{\delta}Y$ has an extra piece of structure, coming from the co-augmentation $\varepsilon_{X}:X\to T\mathfrak{X}$ (adjoint to $\operatorname{Id}_{\mathfrak{X}}$): namely, the counit $\eta_{\mathfrak{X}}=\mathfrak{M}_{{\mathcal{A}}}\varepsilon_{X}:\mathfrak{T}% \mathfrak{X}\to\mathfrak{X}$, which is a splitting for the unit $\xi:\mathfrak{X}\to\mathfrak{T}\mathfrak{X}$ for the monad $\mathfrak{T}$. Any discrete ${\mathcal{A}}$-mapping algebra $\mathfrak{X}$ equipped with a map $\eta_{\mathfrak{X}}:\mathfrak{T}\mathfrak{X}\to\mathfrak{X}$ fitting into a commutative diagram \xymatrix TTX\ar[r]^M_Aε_TX \ar[d]_T(η_X) & TX\ar[d]_η_X TX\ar[r]_η_X & X is called a $\mathfrak{T}$-algebra (cf. [Bor, §4.1].
5.1 Definition. Given a simplicial object $X_{\bullet}\in s{\mathcal{C}}$, over a complete pointed category ${\mathcal{C}}$, recall that its $n$-chains object is ${}C_{n}X_{\bullet}~{}:=~{}\{x\in X_{n}\,|\ d_{i}x=\ast\ \text{for}\ i=1,\dotsc% ,n\}$ ($n\geq 1$), and its $n$-cycles object is: $Z_{n}X_{\bullet}~{}:=~{}\{x\in X_{n}\,|\ d_{i}x=\ast\ \text{for}\ i=0,\dotsc,n% \}~{},$ with $C_{0}X_{\bullet}=Z_{0}X_{\bullet}:=X_{0}$. The map $d_{0}\lvert_{C_{n}X_{\bullet}}:C_{n}X_{\bullet}\to Z_{n-1}X_{\bullet}$ is denoted by $\mathbf{d}_{0}^{X_{n}}$, and $(C_{n}X_{\bullet},\,\mathbf{d}_{0}^{X_{n}})_{n=0}^{\infty}$ is called the Moore chain complex for $X_{\bullet}$.
2.4 Definition. Let ${\mathcal{A}}$ be a collection of homotopy group objects in the pointed simplicial model category ${\mathcal{C}}$, and let $F:{\mathcal{M}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}^{\operatorname{free}}\to{\mathcal{S}}_{\ast}$ (§1.4) be an enriched functor, which can be prolonged to $\tilde{F}:s{\mathcal{M}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}^{\operatorname{free}}\to c{\mathcal{S% }}_{\ast}$. If $\tilde{F}$ preserves weak equivalences (in the above model category $s({\mathcal{S}}_{\ast}^{\mathbf{\Theta}_{{\mathcal{A}}}}$), we call $F$ an ${\mathcal{A}}$-homotopy functor. This will hold, in particular, if $F$ itself preserves all weak equivalences. The total $n$-th order left derived functor ${\mathbb{L}}^{n}F$ of such an $F$, applied to $Y\in{\mathcal{C}}$, is defined to be the simplicial $n$-stem $({\mathbb{L}}^{n}F)Y:={\mathcal{P}}[{n}]\tilde{F}\mathfrak{V}_{\bullet}\in{% \mathcal{S}tem}^{n}_{{\mathbf{\Delta}^{\operatorname{op}}}}$ (cf. §1.6), where $\mathfrak{V}_{\bullet}$ is a resolution of $\mathfrak{M}_{{\mathcal{A}}}Y$ in the ${\mathcal{A}}$-resolution model category structure on $s({\mathcal{S}}_{\ast}^{\mathbf{\Theta}_{{\mathcal{A}}}})$. If $F:({\mathcal{M}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}^{\operatorname{free}})^{\operatorname{op}}\to% {\mathcal{S}}_{\ast}$ is contravariant, its total $n$-th order left derived functor $({\mathbb{L}}^{n}F)Y$ is defined to be the cosimplicial $n$-stem ${\mathcal{P}}[{n}]\tilde{F}\mathfrak{V}_{\bullet}\in{\mathcal{S}tem}^{n}_{{% \mathbf{\Delta}}}$.
4.6 Definition. Let $B$ be a homotopy cogroup object in a pointed simplicial model category ${\mathcal{C}}$, and $C_{\ast}:[0,\infty]\to{\mathcal{C}}$ a fibrant chain complex. For each $n\geq 0$, applying the mapping space functor $\operatorname{map}_{{\mathcal{C}}}(B,-)$ to the fibration sequence (4.3) yields a fibration sequence ${}\operatorname{map}_{{\mathcal{C}}}(B,\,Z_{n}C_{\ast})~{}\xrightarrow{(j_{n})% _{\#}}~{}\operatorname{map}_{{\mathcal{C}}}(B,\,C_{n})~{}\xrightarrow{(% \partial^{\prime}_{n})_{\#}}~{}\operatorname{map}_{{\mathcal{C}}}(B,\,Z_{n-1}C% _{\ast})$ in ${\mathcal{S}}_{\ast}$, and thus a long exact sequence in homotopy groups: ${}\begin{split}\displaystyle\dotsc~{}\longrightarrow&\displaystyle~{}[\Sigma^{% t}B,\,Z_{n}C_{\ast}]~{}\xrightarrow{(j_{n})_{\ast}}~{}[\Sigma^{t}B,\,C_{n}]~{}% \xrightarrow{(\partial^{\prime}_{n})_{\ast}}~{}[\Sigma^{t}B,\,Z_{n-1}C_{\ast}]% ~{}\longrightarrow\\ &\displaystyle~{}[\Sigma^{t-1}B,\,Z_{n}C_{\ast}]~{}\longrightarrow~{}\dotsc~{}% \longrightarrow~{}[B,\,Z_{n-1}C_{\ast}]~{}.\end{split}$ Moreover, for each $t\geq 0$. $([\Sigma^{t}B\,C_{n}],\,(\partial_{n})_{\ast})_{n=0}^{\infty}$ is a chain complex of groups (abelian, if $t\geq 1$), and because $\operatorname{Im}\,(\partial_{n+1})_{\ast}\subseteq\operatorname{Im}\,(j_{n})_% {\ast}=\operatorname{Ker}\,(\partial^{\prime}_{n})_{\#}$, its homology $H_{n}[\Sigma^{t}B,\,C_{\ast}]$ is a group (abelian, if $t\geq 1$). A chain complex map $f:C_{\ast}\to C_{\ast}^{\prime}$ is called a $B$-weak equivalence if for each $n,t\geq 0$, , $f$ induces an isomorphism in $H_{n}[\Sigma^{t}B\,C_{\ast}]$.
1.5 Definition. For any simplicial category ${\mathcal{D}}$, let $P^{n}{\mathcal{D}}$ denote the simplicial category (with the same objects as ${\mathcal{D}}$) obtained from ${\mathcal{D}}$ by applying the $n$-th Postnikov section functor $P^{n}$ to each mapping space in ${\mathcal{D}}$. In particular, given ${\mathcal{A}}\subseteq{\mathcal{C}}$ as in §1.1, we can apply $P^{n}$ to any $\mathbf{\Theta}_{{\mathcal{A}}}$-model $\mathfrak{X}$ to obtain the corresponding $P^{n}\mathbf{\Theta}_{{\mathcal{A}}}$-model $P^{n}\mathfrak{X}$ (§0.3), and define an $n$-${\mathcal{A}}$-mapping algebra to be a (product-preserving) $P^{n}\mathbf{\Theta}_{{\mathcal{A}}}$-model $\mathfrak{V}:P^{n}\mathbf{\Theta}_{{\mathcal{A}}}\to P^{n}{\mathcal{S}}_{\ast}$ such that the natural map $P^{n-1}\mathfrak{V}\{{\Omega B}\}\to\Omega\mathfrak{V}\{{B}\}$ is an isomorphism for every ${\mathcal{B}}\in\mathbf{\Theta}_{{\mathcal{A}}}$. The category of $n$-${\mathcal{A}}$-mapping algebras will be denoted by ${n}\text{-}{{\mathcal{M}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}}$, and the $n$-th Postnikov section functor extends to a functor $P^{n}:{\mathcal{M}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}\to{n}\text{-}{{\mathcal{M}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}}$.
4.4 Definition. A cochain complex is a pointed functor $C^{\ast}:\Gamma^{\operatorname{op}}\to{\mathcal{C}}$ into some pointed category. However, the concept we shall actually need here is that of an $\Omega$-cochain complex in a pointed model category ${\mathcal{C}}$: this consist of a sequence of fibrant cochain windows $(C^{\ast}_{[n]}:[\mathbf{n},\,\mathbf{0}]^{\operatorname{op}}\to{\mathcal{C}})% _{n=1}^{\infty}$, equipped with a (dimension-wise) weak equivalence of $n$-windows: ${}f_{[n]}~{}:~{}\Omega C^{\ast}_{[n]}~{}\longrightarrow~{}\tau_{n}C^{\ast}_{[n% +1]}$ for each $n\geq 1$ (where the truncation functor $\tau_{n}$ is induced by the inclusion $[\mathbf{n},\mathbf{0}]\hookrightarrow[\mathbf{n}+\mathbf{1},\mathbf{0}]$).
4.13 Definition. Given a homotopy cogroup object $B$ in a pointed model category ${\mathcal{C}}$, a fibrant chain complex $C_{\ast}:[0,\infty]\to{\mathcal{C}}$, and $n\geq 0$, an $n$-spectral system for $B$ and $C_{\ast}$ is a collection ${\mathcal{H}}_{(B,C_{\ast})}$ of left $m$-th order chain complex windows $H_{\alpha}$, indexed by all homotopy classes $\alpha\in[\Sigma^{r}B,C_{k+m}]$ for all $r\geq 0$ and $k\geq 1$, such that $m$ is the maximal value $\leq n$ for which such an $m$-th order chain complex window exists for the given class $\alpha$. An $n$-spectral system ${\mathcal{H}}^{(B,C^{\ast})}$ for an $\Omega$-cochain complex $C^{\ast}$ (with respect to $B$) is defined analogously.
3.9 Definition. Let $\mathfrak{Y}$ be a discrete ${\mathcal{A}}$-mapping algebra. For each $B\in{\mathcal{M}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}$ and $\phi\in\mathfrak{Y}\{{B}\}_{0}$, the space of nullhomotopies for $\phi$ is the pullback $N^{\phi}$: $\xymatrix@R=25pt{\ar@{}[drr]|<<<<{\framebox{\scriptsize{PB}}}N^{\phi}\ar[rr]% \ar[d]&&P\mathfrak{Y}\{{B}\}\ar[d]^{p}\\ \{\phi\}\ar[rr]^{<}<<<<<<<<<{\operatorname{inc}}&&\mathfrak{Y}\{{B}\}}$ in ${\mathcal{S}}_{\ast}$. If $\phi\not\sim 0$, then $N^{\phi}=\emptyset$, The dual Stover construction on $\mathfrak{Y}$ is then defined to be the $R$-Stover space: ${}T\mathfrak{Y}~{}:=~{}\ \prod_{B\in{\mathcal{M}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}}\ \prod_{% \phi\in\mathfrak{Y}\{{B}\}_{0}}\ \lim\left(\{PB_{({\Phi})}\}_{\Phi\in N^{\phi}% _{0}}\xrightarrow{\operatorname{proj}}B_{({\phi})}\right)$ (see [BB2, §9.10] and compare [St, §2]). This defines a contravariant functor $T:{\mathcal{M}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}^{\delta}\to{\mathcal{S}}_{\ast}$, which actually takes values in the category $s{R}\text{-}{\mathcal{M}od}$.
6.1 Definition. An ${\mathcal{A}}$-homotopy functor $F:{\mathcal{M}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}^{\operatorname{free}}\to{\mathcal{S}}_{\ast}$ is said to be of degree $k$ if ${\mathbb{L}}^{n}F$ factors through $\widehat{\mathbb{L}}^{n}F:s{(n+k)}\text{-}{{\mathcal{M}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}}\to{% \mathcal{S}}_{\ast}$ for each $n\geq 0$ (cf. §1.5). In light of Theorem 2.8, we say that a functor $G:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{S}}_{\ast}$ is of degree $k$ if $G=F\circ\mathfrak{M}_{{\mathcal{A}}}$ for $F$ of degree $k$. If $F:{\mathcal{M}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}^{\operatorname{free}}\to{\mathcal{S}}_{\ast}$ is an ${\mathcal{A}}$-homotopy functor of degree $k$, we define its reduced $n$-th order derived functor to be $(\widehat{\mathbb{L}}^{n}F)Y:=\widehat{\mathbb{L}}^{n}F\mathfrak{V}_{\bullet}% \in{\mathcal{S}tem}^{n}_{{\mathbf{\Delta}^{\operatorname{op}}}}$, where $\mathfrak{V}_{\bullet}\to P^{n+k}\mathfrak{M}_{{\mathcal{A}}}Y$ is a simplicial resolution in $P^{n+k}{\mathcal{S}}_{\ast}^{P^{n+k}\mathbf{\Theta}_{{\mathcal{A}}}}$.
3.17 Definition. Given an ${\mathcal{A}}$-mapping algebra $\mathfrak{X}$, let $\mathfrak{V}^{\delta}_{\bullet}$ be the functorial simplicial discrete ${\mathcal{A}}$-mapping algebra-resolution of $\mathfrak{X}_{\bullet}$ defined by the comonad $\mathfrak{T}$ (with $\mathfrak{V}_{n}^{\delta}=\mathfrak{T}^{n+1}\mathfrak{X}$), equipped with the augmentation $\eta_{\mathfrak{X}}:\mathfrak{V}^{\delta}_{0}\to\mathfrak{X}_{\bullet}$. Set $\mathfrak{V}_{n}:=\mathfrak{M}_{{\mathcal{A}}}T\mathfrak{T}^{n}\mathfrak{X}$ for all $n\geq 0$. Because $\eta_{\mathfrak{X}}$ lifts to a map of ${\mathcal{A}}$-mapping algebras $\eta:\mathfrak{V}_{0}\to\mathfrak{X}$ (by the proof of Proposition 3.16), the simplicial discrete ${\mathcal{A}}$-mapping algebra $\mathfrak{V}^{\delta}_{\bullet}$ lifts to a simplicial ${\mathcal{A}}$-mapping algebra $\mathfrak{V}_{\bullet}$. Moreover, if we set $W^{0}=T\mathfrak{X}$, and $W^{n}:=T\mathfrak{V}_{n-1}$ for $n\geq 1$, we obtain a cosimplicial space $W^{\bullet}$, with the missing coface map induced by $\eta$ (so $d^{n}:W^{n-1}\to W^{n}$ is $T\mathfrak{T}^{n-1}(\eta)$. This $W^{\bullet}$ is called the dual Stover resolution of $\mathfrak{X}$, and $\mathfrak{V}_{\bullet}=\mathfrak{M}_{{\mathcal{A}}}W^{\bullet}$ by construction. We now define the realization functor $K:{\mathcal{M}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}\to{\mathcal{S}}_{\ast}$ by setting $K\mathfrak{X}:=\operatorname{Tot}(W^{\bullet})$.
5.15 Definition. We call the functorial replacement of $\Omega_{v}\operatorname{Tot}^{n-1}W^{\bullet}\xrightarrow{\partial^{n-1}}% \Omega_{v}^{n}N^{n}W^{\bullet}\xrightarrow{j^{({n})}}\operatorname{Tot}^{n}W^{\bullet}$ by: $\Omega_{v}\widehat{\Omega^{n}NW^{\bullet}}\xrightarrow{\Omega_{v}\widehat{j}^{% ({n})}}\Omega_{v}\operatorname{Tot}^{n}W^{\bullet}\hookrightarrow\Omega_{v}^{n% +1}N^{n+1}W^{\bullet}$ the fibrant $n$-strictification, and the composite $\widehat{\Omega^{n}\delta}\,\!^{n}$ is called the fibrant $n$-coface map.
3.1 Definition. If ${\mathcal{A}}$ is any collection of homotopy group objects in a simplicial category ${\mathcal{C}}$, a discrete ${\mathcal{A}}$-mapping algebra is a function $\mathfrak{Y}:{\mathcal{A}}\to{\mathcal{S}}_{\ast}$, (again written $B\mapsto\mathfrak{Y}\{{B}\}$), equipped with isomorphisms $\theta_{B}:\mathfrak{Y}\{{\Omega B}\}\to\Omega\mathfrak{Y}\{{B}\}$ for each $B\in{\mathcal{A}}$. We can of course extend it to a function on $\operatorname{Obj}\mathbf{\Theta}_{{\mathcal{A}}}$ by requiring it to preserve products. The category of discrete ${\mathcal{A}}$-mapping algebras is denoted by ${\mathcal{M}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}^{\delta}$, with the forgetful functor $U:{\mathcal{M}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}\to{\mathcal{M}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}^{\delta}$. We write $\mathfrak{X}_{\delta}$ for $U\mathfrak{X}$ and $\mathfrak{M}_{{\mathcal{A}}}^{\delta}$ for $U\circ\mathfrak{M}_{{\mathcal{A}}}$.
4.9 Definition. For $B$ and $C_{\ast}$ as above, the long exact sequences (4.8), for various $n\geq 1$, fit together to yield an exact couple. We call the (homological) spectral sequence associated to this exact couple the spectral sequence of $C_{\ast}$ (with respect to $B$), with $E^{2}_{m,t}~{}=~{}H_{m}[\Sigma^{t}B\,C_{\ast}]~{}.$ We do not address the issue of convergence (or abutment) of this spectral sequence. The (cohomological) spectral sequence of an $\Omega$- cochain complex $C^{\ast}$ (with respect to $B$) is defined analogously, with the indexing taking the shift map (4.5) into account, so that $E_{2}^{m,t}~{}=~{}H^{m}[\Sigma^{t}B\,\Omega^{m}C^{\ast}_{[m]}]~{}\cong~{}H^{m}% \pi_{t-m}\operatorname{map}(B\,C^{\ast}_{[m]})~{}.$ Here $H^{m}[\Sigma^{t}B\,\Omega^{m}C^{\ast}_{[m]}]$ is the cohomology of the obvious cochain complex (in groups). A weak equivalence of $\Omega$-cochain complexes is defined analogously to §4.6.
