Définition 4 Un élément de Maurer-Cartan (M-C) pour $E\in Ob(\mathcal{P})$ est un élément $\eta\in\mathcal{P}^{1}(E,E)$ vérifiant l’équation de Courbure suivante $\delta(\eta)+\eta.\eta=0$ on définit l’ensemble $Ob(MC({\mathcal{P}}))$ comme l’ensemble des couples $(E,\eta)$ où $E\in Ob(\mathcal{P})$ et $\eta$ est un élément de Maurer-Cartan. Un tel couple sera appelé $MC$-objet
Definition 3.1. Let $R$ be a commutative ring with unit. We say $R$ is absolutely flat (also known as von Neumann regular) if for every $r\in R$ there exists some $x\in R$ satisfying $r=r^{2}x.$
Definition 2.13. Let $X$ be a spectral space. We denote by $X^{\mathrm{con}}$ the set $X$ equipped with the constructible topology which is given by taking the quasi-compact open subsets of $X$ and their complements as a subbasis of open sets. A subset $Z$ of $X$ which is closed in the constructible topology is called proconstructible.
Definition 4.8. A localising subcategory $\mathcal{L}$ of $\mathsf{D}(R)$ is a Bousfield class if there is an $X\in\mathsf{D}(R)$ such that $\mathcal{L}=\{Y\in\mathsf{D}(R)\;|\;X\otimes Y\cong 0\}=\ker(X\otimes(-)).$ The localising subcategory $\mathcal{L}$ is a cohomological Bousfield class if there is an $X\in\mathsf{D}(R)$ such that $\mathcal{L}=\{Y\in\mathsf{D}(R)\;|\;\operatorname{Hom}(Y,\Sigma^{i}X)=0\;\;% \forall i\in\mathbb{Z}\}={}^{\perp}X.$ We call $\ker(X\otimes(-))$ the Bousfield class of $X$ and ${}^{\perp}X$ the cohomological Bousfield class of $X$.
Definition 3.6. Let $A$ be an acyclic category. A functor $\mu:A\rightarrow\mathbb{N}$ satisfying $\mu(x)<\mu(y)$ for $x<y$ in Ob$(A)$ is called an $\mathbb{N}$-filtration of $A$. A pair $(A,\mu)$ is called an $\mathbb{N}$-filtered acyclic category.
Definition 3.4. A small category $A$ is acyclic if every endomorphism and every isomorphism is an identity morphism.
Definition 3.7. Let $(A,\mu)$ be an $\mathbb{N}$-filtered acyclic category. Then, define $\chi_{\text{fil}}(A,\mu)$ as follows. For natural numbers $i$ and $n$, let $\overline{N_{n}}(A)_{i}=\{\mathbf{f}\in\overline{N_{n}}(A)\mid\mu(t(\mathbf{f}% ))=i\}$ where $t(\mathbf{f})=x_{n}$ if $\mathbf{f}=\xymatrix{(x_{0}\ar[r]^{f_{1}}&x_{1}\ar[r]^{f_{2}}&\dots\ar[r]^{f_{% n}}&x_{n})}.$ Suppose each $\overline{N_{n}}(A)_{i}$ is finite. Define the formal power series $f_{\chi}(A,\mu)(t)$ over $\mathbb{Z}$ by $f_{\chi}(A,\mu)(t)=\sum^{\infty}_{i=0}(-1)^{i}\left(\sum^{i}_{n=0}(-1)^{n}\#% \overline{N_{n}}(A)_{i}\right)t^{i}.$ Then, define $\chi_{\text{fil}}(A,\mu)=f_{\chi}(A,\mu)|_{t=-1}$ if $f_{\chi}(A,\mu)(t)$ is rational and has a non-vanishing denominator at $t=-1$.
Definition 5 An action of the group $GL_{l}(K)$ on a generalized $2$-vector space ${\cal B}$ is called smooth if the following condition is satisfied. For any objects $E$, $D$ from ${\cal B}$ and for any morphism $f\in\mathop{\rm Hom}\nolimits_{{\cal B}}(E,D)$ there are an integer $m\geq 0$, objects $(E,\theta)$ and $(D,\vartheta)$ from the category ${\cal B}^{{\mathbb{C}}_{m}}$ such that $f\in\mathop{\rm Hom}_{{\cal B}^{{\mathbb{C}}_{m}}}((E,\theta), (D,\vartheta))$.
Definition 3 Let ${\cal B}$ be a $k$-linear category with a $G$-action. A category of $G$-equivariant objects ${\cal B}^{G}$ is defined as follows. 1. An object of the category ${\cal B}^{G}$ consists of an object $E$ of the category ${\cal B}$ and of a system of isomorphisms: $\theta_{g}\;:\;E\longrightarrow\tau(g)(E)\quad\mbox{for any}\quad g\in G\mbox{,}$ such that the following diagram is commutative for any elements $g,h\in G$: $\diagram E&\rTo^{\theta_{g}}&\tau(g)(E)\\ \dTo^{\theta_{gh}}&&\dTo_{\tau(g)(\theta_{h})}\\ \tau(gh)(E)&\lTo_{\psi_{g,h,E}}&\tau(g)(\tau(h)(E))$ 2. A morphism of equivariant objects $\,:\,(E,\theta)\longrightarrow(D,\vartheta)$ is a morphism $f\in\mathop{\rm Hom}_{{\cal B}}(E,D)$ such that $\tau(g)(f)\,\theta_{g}=\vartheta_{g}f$.
Definition 1 An action of a group $G$ on a $k$-linear category $\cal B$ consists of the following data. 1. For every element $g\in G$ there is a $k$-linear functor $\tau(g)\,:\,\cal B\to\cal B$. 2. For every pair of elements $g,h\in G$ there is an isomorphism of functors $\psi_{g,h}\,:\,\tau(g)\circ\tau(h)\Rightarrow\tau(gh)$. 3. There is an isomorphism of functors $\psi_{1}\,:\,\tau(1)\Rightarrow\mathop{\rm Id}_{\cal B}$. Besides, the following conditions are satisfied. 1. For any $g,h,k\in G$ the associativity holds: $\psi_{gh,k}(\psi_{g,h}\circ\tau(k))=\psi_{g,hk}(\tau(g)\circ\psi_{h,k})$. 2. For any $g\in G$ formulas $\psi_{1,g}=\psi_{1}\circ\tau(g)$ and $\psi_{g,1}=\tau(g)\circ\psi(1)$ hold.
Definition 4 We say that a category ${\cal B}$ is a generalized $2$-vector space over a field $k$, if ${\cal B}$ is a $k$-linear abelian category. We say that the category ${\cal B}$ has finite dimension $r$, if the category ${\cal B}$ is equivalent to the category $(\mathop{\rm Vect}_{k}^{\rm fin})^{r}$.
Definition 2 Let $\cal B$ and $\cal C$ be $k$-linear categories with a $G$-action. A $G$-linear functor $\mathfrak{T}=(T,\varepsilon)$ from ${\cal B}$ to ${\cal C}$ consists of the following data. 1. There is a $k$-linear functor $T\,:\,{\cal B}\to{\cal C}$. 2. For any element $g\in G$ there is an isomorphism of functors $\varepsilon_{g}\,:\,T\circ\tau_{{\cal B}}(g)\Rightarrow\tau_{{\cal C}}(g)\circ T$. Besides, the following conditions are satisfied. 1. For any elements $g,h\in G$ the following diagram is commutative: {diagram} T ∘τB(g) ∘τB(h) && \rImpliesT ∘ψB, g, h & & T ∘τB (g h) \dImpliesεg∘τB(h) & & & & \dImpliesεgh τC(g) ∘T ∘τB(h) & \rImpliesτC(g) ∘εh & τC(g) ∘τC(h) ∘T & \rImpliesψC,g,h∘T & τC(g h) ∘T 2. A formula $(\psi_{{\cal C},1}\circ T)\,\varepsilon_{1}=T\circ\psi_{{\cal B},1}$ holds.
Definition 4 Let $(\mu_{i})_{i=1}^{l}$ and $(\nu_{j})_{j=1}^{m}$ be two partitions of $n$. A refinement from $\overrightarrow{\nu}$ to $\overrightarrow{\mu}$ is a function $r:\{1,\ldots,l\}\rightarrow\{1,\ldots m\}$ such that $\nu_{j}=\sum_{r(i)=j}\mu_{i}$ for every $j$. (Note that the reindexing function is in the opposite direction to the refinement.)
Definition 1 With the notation as above, $p$ is a fibration if $\lambda_{\top}$ has a right adjoint $\rho_{\top}$ over $B^{\mathbb{S}}$, with its counit an equality, and is an opfibration if $\rho_{\bot}$ has a left adjoint $\lambda_{\bot}$ over $B^{\mathbb{S}}$, with its unit an equality.
Definition (Quiver map, [graphtransformation, Definition 2.4]). Given quivers $G$ and $H$, a quiver homomorphism from $G$ to $H$ is a pair $\left(\phi_{V},\phi_{E}\right)$, where $\phi_{V}\in\mathbf{Set}\left(V_{G},V_{H}\right)$ and $\phi_{E}\in\mathbf{Set}\left(E_{G},E_{H}\right)$ satisfy $\phi_{V}\circ\sigma_{G}=\sigma_{H}\circ\phi_{E}$ and $\phi_{V}\circ\tau_{G}=\tau_{H}\circ\phi_{E}$. The function $\phi_{V}$ is the vertex map, and $\phi_{E}$ the edge map.
Definition. Given a quiver $G$, a blow-up of $G$ is a quiver $H$ equipped with partitions $\left(A_{v}\right)_{v\in V(G)}$ of $V(H)$ and $\left(B_{e}\right)_{e\in E(G)}$ of $E(H)$ satisfying 1. $\sigma_{H}(f)\in A_{\sigma_{G}(e)}$, 2. $\tau_{H}(f)\in A_{\tau_{G}(e)}$, 3. $\operatorname{edges}_{H}(x,y)\cap B_{e}\neq\emptyset$, for all $e\in E(G)$, $f\in B_{e}$, $x\in A_{\sigma_{G}(e)}$, $y\in A_{\tau_{G}(e)}$.
Definition (Quiver, [graphtransformation, Definition 2.1]). A quiver is a quadruple $(V,E,\sigma,\tau)$, where ${V,E\in\operatorname{Ob}(\mathbf{Set})}$ are sets, and $\sigma,\tau\in\mathbf{Set}(E,V)$ are functions. Elements of $V$ are vertices, and $V$ the vertex set. Elements of $E$ are edges, and $E$ the edge set. The function $\sigma$ is the source map, and $\tau$ the target map. For $e\in E$, $\sigma(e)$ is the source of $e$, and $\tau(e)$ the target of $e$.
Definition ([grilliette3, Definition 3.1.1]). For a quiver $J$ and $v,w\in V(J)$, let $\operatorname{edges}_{J}(v,w):=\sigma_{J}^{-1}(v)\cap\tau_{J}^{-1}(w)$ be the set of all edges in $J$ with source $v$ and target $w$. A quiver $J$ is loaded if for every $v,w\in V(J)$, $\operatorname{edges}_{J}(v,w)\neq\emptyset$.
Definition 5.1. Let $\mathscr{X}$ be a contravariantly finite (or covariantly finite) extension-closed subcategory of a triangulated category $\mathcal{C}$ and let $\mathcal{D}$ be a subcategory of $\mathscr{X}$. We call that $\mathcal{D}$ is a $\mathscr{X}-$cluster tilting subcategory provided that $\mathcal{D}$ is functorially finite in $\mathscr{X}$, and satisfies that for any object $D\in\mathscr{X}$, $M\in\mathcal{D}$ if and only if $Ext^{1}(\mathcal{D},M)=0$ if and only if $Ext^{1}(M,\mathcal{D})=0$. An object $D$ in $\mathscr{X}$ is called a $\mathscr{X}-$cluster tilting object if $\mbox{add}D$ is a $\mathscr{X}-$cluster tilting subcategory.
Definition 5.6. We call the cotorsion pair $(\mu^{-1}(\mathscr{X};\mathcal{D}),\mu^{-1}(\mathscr{Y};\mathcal{D}))$ is a $\mathcal{D}-$mutation of cotorsion pair $(\mathscr{X},\mathscr{Y})$. Sometimes denote this cotorsion pair by $(\mathscr{X}^{\prime},\mathscr{Y}^{\prime})$, denote its core by $I^{\prime}$.
Definition 3.14. A basic rigid object $T$ in $\mathcal{C}$ is called connected provided $T$ cannot written as $T=T_{1}\oplus T_{2}$ with property that $T_{i}\not=0$, and $Hom(T_{i},T_{j})=0$, for $i\neq j\in\{1,2\}$. Any cluster tilting object in $\mathcal{C}$ can be decomposed as a direct sum of connected summands: $T=\oplus_{i=1}^{m}T_{i}$ with $T_{i}$ being connected. We call such decomposition a complete decomposition of $T$.
Definition 3.3. Let $\mathcal{T}$ be a $d-$cluster tilting subcategory of a triangulated category $\mathcal{C}$, and $\mathcal{T}_{i},i\in I,$ be subcategories of $\mathcal{T}$. We call that $\mathcal{T}$ is a direct sum of subcategories $\mathcal{T}_{i},i\in I,$ provided that $1.$ Any object $T\in\mathcal{T}$ is a direct sum of finitely many objects $T_{i}\in\mathcal{T}_{i}$; $2.$ $\mbox{Hom}(\mathcal{T}_{i},\mathcal{T}_{j})=0,\forall i\neq j$; $3.$ $\mbox{Hom}(\mathcal{T}_{i}[k],\mathcal{T}_{j})=0,\forall i\neq j,1\leq k\leq d-2$; In this case, we write $\mathcal{T}=\oplus_{i\in I}\mathcal{T}_{i}$. We say $\mathcal{T}$ is indecomposable if $\mathcal{T}$ cannot be written as a direct sum of two nonzero subcategories.
Definition 3.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a triangulated category, $d>1$, an integer. A subcategory $\mathcal{T}$ of $\mathcal{C}$ is called $d-$rigid provided $\mbox{Ext}^{i}(\mathcal{T},\mathcal{T})=0$ for all $1\leq i\leq d-1$. A $d-$ rigid subcategory $\mathcal{T}$ is called $d-$cluster tilting provided that $\mathcal{T}$ is functorially finite, and satisfies the property: $T\in\mathcal{T}$ if and only if $\mbox{Ext}^{i}(\mathcal{T},T)=0$ for all $1\leq i\leq d-1$ if and only if $\mbox{Ext}^{i}(T,\mathcal{T})=0$ for all $1\leq i\leq d-1;$ An object $T$ is called a $d-$cluster tilting (respectively $d-$rigid) object if $addT$ is $d-$cluster tilting (respectively $d-$rigid).
Definition 3.2. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a triangulated category, and $\mathcal{C}_{i},i\in I$ be triangulated subcategories of $\mathcal{C}$. We call that $\mathcal{C}$ is a direct sum of triangulated subcategories $\mathcal{C}_{i},i\in I,$ provided that $1.$ Any object $M\in\mathcal{C}$ is a direct sum of finitely many objects $M_{i}\in\mathcal{C}_{i}$; $2.$ $\mbox{Hom}(\mathcal{C}_{i},\mathcal{C}_{j})=0,\forall i\neq j$. In this case, we write $C=\oplus_{i\in I}\mathcal{C}_{i}$. We say $\mathcal{C}$ is indecomposable if $\mathcal{C}$ cannot be written as a direct sum of two nonzero triangulated subcategories.
